Proceedings into the SABC board's fitness to hold office wrapped up for the year on Thursday and will resume in January. CAPE TOWN - The Democratic Alliance (DA) says the 'no-holds barred manner' in which the SABC ad hoc committee has conducted the hearings should serve as a warning for other parastatals.Proceedings wrapped up for the year today and will resume in January.Communications Minister Faith Muthambi, members of the so-called SABC 8 and lone board member and chairperson Mbulaheni Maguvhe were among the witnesses who delivered explosive evidence before the committee this week.Committee member and DA shadow communications minister Phumzile van Damme said: Some of the shocking revelations include the fact that the State Security Agency was brought in to investigate and spy on staff. &quot;Revelations such as that the Minister of Communications interfered in the affairs of the board, also in the manner in which the SABC covered the news. She adds she will be delving through hundreds of documents ahead of next year's hearings. We will now look through the 577 documents that the SABC has provided to the committee and then decide on what steps need to be taken going forward. (Edited by Neo Koza)